import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="PSALM — Method">
  <section>
    <h2>The idea, plainly</h2>
    <p>
      A child learns language from a few million words, not a few trillion. PSALM
      borrows that spirit. Instead of pouring more text into a small model, we give
      it a short, dense lesson in <em>structure</em> first — generated by Pāṇini's
      grammar of Sanskrit — and only then let it read ordinary English. The
      experiment asks a sharp question: when the total amount of text is held
      fixed, does the kind of structural lesson you start with change how well the
      model ends up understanding language?
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>One model, read three ways</h2>
    <p>
      A single small bidirectional encoder is trained once and evaluated along
      three axes: English structural generalization on the public BabyLM
      benchmarks, Sanskrit linguistic competence on morphology and word-order
      tasks, and the cross-lingual gap between a grammar-primed model and a plain
      baseline. The model does not choose an identity; it is trained on all three
      signals and measured on all three, so the same weights answer the
      competition question and the scientific one.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The four-arm, token-matched test</h2>
    <p>
      The heart of the study is an ablation in which four conditions share one
      English pretraining corpus and differ only in the structural dose given
      beforehand, with every dose trimmed to the same token budget. The English
      dose is a control that holds budget fixed while contributing no foreign
      structure; the Pāṇinian dose carries grammatical form with gold kāraka
      roles; the Dyck dose carries hierarchy without meaning; and the Paribhāṣā
      dose carries typed Navya-Nyāya semantic graphs. Because the budget is
      identical, any difference at the end belongs to the dose and not to how much
      text was read.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Arm</th><th>Dose</th><th>What it isolates</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>A</td><td>English (control)</td><td>budget held fixed, no foreign structure</td></tr>
        <tr><td>B</td><td>Pāṇinian Sanskrit</td><td>grammatical form + kāraka roles</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C</td><td>k-Shuffle Dyck</td><td>hierarchy without semantics</td></tr>
        <tr><td>D</td><td>Paribhāṣā graphs</td><td>typed semantic structure</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The Śabdabodha pipeline</h2>
    <p>
      Arm D's dose is produced automatically. Every generated Sanskrit sentence is
      parsed for its kāraka structure by the Vidyut engine, converted by
      Vyutpattivāda rules into a typed semantic graph, and linearized into a string
      the model can read — a deterministic path from sentence to meaning that needs
      no human annotation. This is the project's most distinctive engineering
      contribution: a grammar and a logic, together, manufacturing their own
      supervised data.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Leaderboard submission: H1_MECHANISM</h2>
    <p>
      The ablation arms isolate dose type; a separate submission track layers six
      Pāṇinian-inspired mechanisms throughout all 10M tokens of pretraining.
      These mechanisms are never applied to arms A–D, so the ablation is uncontaminated.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Mechanism</th><th>What it does</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Vidyut N-hot embeddings</td>
          <td>10-dimensional binary morpheme-boundary feature per BPE token; linear
          projection to 768d, summed with token embedding at every layer</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>BPE-heuristic kāraka masking</td>
          <td>Word-initial tokens → kartā (p=0.50); derivational suffixes → viśeṣaṇa
          (p=0.20); sub-word fragments → separator (p=0.10); vectorized GPU gather
          applied at every step</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Salience transfer</td>
          <td>Empirical masking frequencies from dose-priming Stage 1 become a soft
          prior for Stage 2; structures that were hard to predict during Sanskrit
          training receive more attention during English pretraining</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Muon optimizer</td>
          <td>Newton–Schulz orthogonalization of gradient momentum on all 2-D weight
          matrices; embeddings and layer norms use AdamW</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Progressive sequence length</td>
          <td>Training sequence grows 64 → 128 → 256, allocating early GPU capacity
          to local morpho-syntactic patterns before full-sentence context</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Cosine mask decay</td>
          <td>Masking probability decreases 0.30 → 0.15 over training; the model
          trains harder on rare-token structure early and relaxes as it learns</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      BabyLM 2026 compliance: 3 dose epochs + 7 English epochs (= 10, the
      published maximum). Developmental checkpoints are saved at every 1M-word
      interval to 10M, and at every 10M thereafter — enabling a sample-efficiency
      learning-curve analysis. Pre-registered threshold: BLiMP ≥ 70.0 on the
      official zero-shot suite (≥ 3 seeds, mean ± 95% CI, Holm–Bonferroni).
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>H2: Navya-Nyāya post-pretraining</h2>
    <p>
      After the 10M-word pretraining, the best H1_MECHANISM arm is fine-tuned using
      LoRA adapters (rank 16, QKV projections) on 75 Pañcāvayava inference chains from
      the pramana dataset. Each chain encodes a six-phase Navya-Nyāya scaffold:
      pratijñā (thesis), hetu (reason), udāharaṇa (example), upanaya (application),
      nigamana (conclusion), plus tarka (tautological reduction) and hetvābhāsa
      (fallacy detection). A Z3 SMT vyāpti verifier validates the entailment steps
      before inclusion. The synergy test measures sample efficiency: how many examples
      does PSALM + Nyāya need to reach 80% NLI accuracy, compared to a Generic-1B
      baseline + Nyāya?
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>How we measure, and how we stay honest</h2>
    <p>
      Minimal-pair and world-knowledge tasks are scored without task-specific heads
      by reading pseudo-log-likelihoods directly off the masked model, and the
      (Super)GLUE tasks are read with a light classifier fine-tune. Every reported
      contrast carries bootstrap confidence intervals and Holm–Bonferroni
      correction against thresholds fixed before the numbers were computed. The
      ablation arms (A–D) are strictly separated from the submission track mechanisms,
      so the scientific comparison is never contaminated by leaderboard tuning.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
